SUMMARY:Scarlett (Rong) He PhD Completion Seminar
DTSTART:20260218T110000
DTEND:20260218T120000
DESCRIPTION:Presenter:Scarlett (Rong) He\n\nSupervisors:David Pitt\, Shuan
 ming Li\, Zhuo Jin (Macquarie Business School)\n\nTitle:Data-Driven Actuar
 ial Modelling of Cyber Risk: Frequency\, Severity\, and Insurance Pricing\
 n\nDay/Time:Wednesday 18 February 2026\, 11am - 12pm Australian Eastern Da
 ylight Time Time (AEDT)\n\nVenue:FBE-304\n\nZoom Link:https://unimelb.zoom
 .us/j/89762547188?pwd=5D8zMxbyg70viHWcZSaVNaRrnaxRZK.1(Password: 414939)\n
 \nAbstract:\n\nThis thesis investigates cyber risk through an integrated f
 ramework that links loss occurrence\, loss severity\, and insurance decisi
 on making under realistic information availability situations. Aninterdisc
 iplinary survey first synthesises existing research across fields includin
 g computer science\, business and economics\, and actuarial studies\, high
 lighting fragmentation in current approaches and motivating the need for u
 nified modelling frameworks.\n\nBuilding on these insights\, cyber loss fr
 equency is reinterpreted through an epidemic lens that captures temporal a
 nd feature dependent propagation dynamics\, while loss severity is studied
  using both distributional approaches and modern machine learning and deep
  learning methods\, taking into consideration that incident-specific chara
 cteristics are unobservable at the time of underwriting. Finally\, predict
 ive outputs are embedded into a reinforcement learning framework that expl
 ores deductible and coverage limit design under alternative pricing settin
 gs. The results from these studies demonstrate that epidemic-informed freq
 uency models improve incident count prediction\, that predicted incident t
 ypes can serve as an informative feature with only marginal loss of accura
 cy in severity prediction\, and that these predictive components can be ma
 pped into practical insurance contract design under different pricing obje
 ctives through a reinforcement learning module.\n\nOverall\, the thesis en
 riches actuarial modelling of cyber risk by drawing on epidemic processes 
 to accommodate cyber risk propagation and by bridging predictive analysis 
 and insurance decision making under the practical constraints of cyber ins
 urance markets
URL:https://fbe.unimelb.edu.au/economics/events/seminars/scarlett-rong-he-
 phd-completion-seminar
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
